  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves disguising the origins of money obtained through criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other illicit means.\n\nLaws against money laundering are designed to prevent criminals from profiting from their illegal activities and to protect the integrity of financial systems. Many countries have strict regulations and enforcement mechanisms in place, including the requirement for financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and to maintain anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n\nInternational cooperation, such as through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), also plays a critical role in combating money laundering by setting global standards and encouraging countries to implement effective AML measures. Violations of money laundering laws can lead to severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
